or dynamic class loading with arbitrary strings, it might lead to UnsupportedFeatureError. The instructions mention catching errors for dynamic loading, but since this involves ordinary reflection metadata, I'm aiming to determine if canLoad can handle such missing classes properly.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Investigating class loading issues**\\n\\nI’m considering how to broaden the catch in the library. I could include a fake IBM class, but that would break the rule against stubs or shadows. I can't cover line 71 unless it's an actual IBM class. Maybe I can address the canLoad line without setting IBM by invoking a private method, but direct reflection is off the table.  \\n\\nI’m also worried about issues with the system property java.vendor=\\\"IBM\\\" if the class initializes before the property. This draws up questions about the Java class loading process, especially with KerberosError. There are complications with JIT and native image builds too, which could affect method invocation. I need to ensure that tests are created or updated properly within the target project directory. Maybe inspecting dynamic access coverage JSON could help clarify things.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_bw5ZlXLjTXNwZY71PRNQsyJ2|fc_001d093e6ef2bd43016a0f3749f3608195b9242255d244e1b4", "name": "read", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/org.apache.kafka/kafka-clients/4.2.0/build/reports/dynamic-access/dynamic-access-coverage.json", "limit": 80}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 792, "output": 968, "cacheRead": 22528, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 24288, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1779382070754, "responseId": "resp_001d093e6ef2bd43016a0f3737388c8195a148d17d44351128"}}
