or each test class, but what if the upstream test is using JUnit 4? The existing OrgApacheKafkaCommonNetworkSaslChannelBuilderTestTest calls `new SaslChannelBuilderTest()` in a Jupiter test after the extension. Maybe the JUnit extension service isn’t functioning properly because the `junit-platform.properties` resource is missing in the native setup?\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating testing setup**\\n\\nI'm working through the testing process and noticing that `./gradlew test` seems to invoke `nativeTest` instead of `javaTest`. The progress report might be tied to the Forge dynamic coverage workflow. The user only encounters an error with native compilation. I have to follow the Native Image test rules. It's possible to configure tasks for better performance, but they might still run slowly. Maybe I could create a dedicated test that leverages the public API and prioritize it with a JUnit class orderer.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating image processing options**\\n\\nI’m considering the effectiveness of an agent that was previously used. It seems like it hasn’t had a significant effect, so maybe I can remove it to simplify things. In dealing with native images, I notice there’s no agent involved; perhaps an extension might do the trick, but it didn't seem to work before. Still, I wonder if it could do any good without causing any harm.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering build.gradle options**\\n\\nI'm exploring how `junit-platform.properties` and the service could affect all tests. Is it necessary to keep it? The agent might be enough. For native images, the extension may still set properties too early. I need to add the agent class and edit `build.gradle`. \\n\\nThe `systemProperty \\\"java.vendor\\\"` might be redundant but isn't harmful. However, I’m not sure if it gets ignored. Should I remove it to avoid confusion, or keep it? I’ll inspect the current `build.gradle` for options.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_mZ2LwoRH85nnFwzNYwOkHi4z|fc_001d093e6ef2bd43016a0f3a000d788195ae61faf5772e962c", "name": "write", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/org.apache.kafka/kafka-clients/4.2.0/src/test/java/org_apache_kafka/kafka_clients/KerberosVendorAgent.java", "content": "/*\n * Copyright and related rights waived via CC0\n *\n * You should have received a copy of the CC0 legalcode along with this\n * work. If not, see <http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/>.\n */\npackage org_apache_kafka.kafka_clients;\n\nimport java.lang.instrument.Instrumentation;\n\npublic final class KerberosVendorAgent {\n\n    private KerberosVendorAgent() {\n    }\n\n    public static void premain(String agentArgs, Instrumentation instrumentation) {\n        System.setProperty(\"java.vendor\", \"IBM Corporation\");\n    }\n}\n"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 5145, "output": 3972, "cacheRead": 40448, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 49565, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1779382723986, "responseId": "resp_001d093e6ef2bd43016a0f39c520b0819582de2e653ec24086"}}
