mgubvgcMK9RYNCI2d0sPPh_xGU_OAAb8=\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering test configuration**\\n\\nI'm thinking about creating a dedicated Kerberos test file, and I wonder if a suitable class name could be structured as `AOrg...KerberosErrorTest`. It seems like one-to-one mapping doesn’t necessitate exact naming, though. I'm also toying with renaming the test to `AOrgApacheKafkaCommonSecurityKerberosKerberosErrorTest` for alphabetical precedence, but that may complicate the naming logic. Perhaps configuring a JUnit class orderer to prioritize it would be a simpler approach. It can set properties before discovery to ensure it runs first.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating testing solutions**\\n\\nI'm considering if a solution could address both native and JVM environments without needing a javaagent, assuming no class initialization occurs during discovery. But what if discovery initializes Kafka test classes? That seems unlikely, though I want to be thorough. I might need a support class for robustness, but is it actually necessary for native? The last extension attempt failed even though it should have set the property before each class. I'm curious why that happened.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_wvQKodadi4e4gpBJitT1x4yH|fc_001d093e6ef2bd43016a0f3a1d4f648195974dd9c0610ef468", "name": "read", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/org.apache.kafka/kafka-clients/4.2.0/src/test/java/org_apache_kafka/kafka_clients/KafkaClientsTest.java", "offset": 220, "limit": 120}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 886, "output": 1408, "cacheRead": 49152, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 51446, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1779382789347, "responseId": "resp_001d093e6ef2bd43016a0f3a060f648195bfe9d5579e478b2a"}}
